                  Tsunamis

   They are started by offshore earthquakes, volcanic eruptions, landslides and
   other seismic or tectonic events. They can race along the ocean floor at
   speeds up to 500 miles per hour, undetectable from the surface. But when they
   reach the shore, the underwater waves turn their speed into height, and can
   rise some 70 feet above the water's surface, crashing into the coastline with
   enough force to obliterate entire communities. Called tsunamis, the Japanese
   word for "harbor waves," they have claimed 50,000 lives in the past century
   alone, making them one of the deadliest forms of natural disasters.
